ess with authorization2star  aThe word “blood” awakens ancient ideas, but we know little about its historical representation in Western cultures. Anthropologists have customarily studied how societies think about the bodily substances that unite them, and the contributors to this volume develop those questions in new directions. Taking a radically historical perspective that complements traditional cultural analyses, they demonstrate how blood and kinship have constantly been reconfigured in European culture. This volume challenges the idea that blood can be understood as a stable entity, and shows how concepts of blood and kinship moved in both parallel and divergent directions over the course of European history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aBloodxSymbolic aspectszEurope. 0aFamilieszEurope. 0aKinshipzEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aAubert, Guillaume, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarsten, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelille, Gérard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEssner, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuerreau-Jalabert, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarders, Ann-Cathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Christopher H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Christopher H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJussen, Bernhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoreau, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuiz, 